snippet.textDisplay: My eyes bled watching the crimping of that pasty.   Making a pasty is one of the easiest things on the planet.  Get a circle of puff pastry, fill with a mix of chopped steak 400g, onions150g, potato 300g and suede 150g, add a bunch of black pepper and salt, fold in half, crimp. Cook for 50 minutes @165c.

Get a circle of puff pastry, fill with a mix of chopped steak 400g, onions150g, potato 300g and suede 150g, add a bunch of black pepper and salt, fold in half, crimp. Cook for 50 minutes @165c.

snippet.textDisplay: According to Paul Hollywood you need 21 crimps in order to be a traditional English pasty - Well, I don't know about English pasties, but the guy has no clue how to crimp a Cornish pasty. The technique is completely wrong. The look is wrong and there is no set number. I'm a Cornishman who has worked in a Cornish bakery btw. Also, rutabaga? That is the first time in my life I have ever seen one. They are not used in Cornish pasties. Also, in Cornwall, swedes are called turnips, and those are what you use. Finally, you don't use sliced vegetables. You use diced, and everything is mixed together. not layered. So yeah. Typical English failure to make a decent Cornish pasty.

snippet.textDisplay:
Uh... cornish pasties were pocket food for miners in the Cornwall region. They're basically poor man leftovers wrapped in piecrust to make them easy to carry. They're not 'gourmet' food and there's no 'standard' pastie - other than they should have potatoes, swede and onions.
I've seen them made both by precooking the filling and by just putting the ingredients in the crust. Both are fine.

I'm amused that he keeps wanting to up it by adding white wine. Not a bad idea - but not typical.

I've seen them made both by precooking the filling and by just putting the ingredients in the crust. Both are fine.
